</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="27" pageNumber="150" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="27" pageNumber="150">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="27" pageNumber="150">
Morphologically, 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. fastigiata" order="Poales" pageId="27" pageNumber="150" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="fastigiata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="150">M. fastigiata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can sometimes be confused with the distantly related 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. ligularis" order="Poales" pageId="27" pageNumber="150" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="ligularis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="150">M. ligularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName authority="subg. Bealia" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" infraspecific-rank="subg." kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M." order="Poales" pageId="27" pageNumber="150" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="genus" subGenus="Bealia">M. subg. Bealia</taxonomicName>
; Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="F1" captionText="Figure 1. A, B Maximum-likelihood tree inferred from combined plastid (ndhA intron, rps 16 - trnK, rps 16 intron, rps 3, and rpl 32 - trnL) and ITS sequences. Thick branches indicate posterior probabilities of 0.95 - 1; species in red occur in South America; scale bar = 2 %." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.114.28799.figure1" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/254042" pageId="27" pageNumber="150">1B</figureCitation>
). However, the former has well developed rhizomes (absent in 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. ligularis" order="Poales" pageId="27" pageNumber="150" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="ligularis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="150">M. ligularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and tightly involute, acuate leaf blades (versus flat and straight). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rydb" authorityYear="1905" baseAuthorityName="Trin." class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Muhlenbergia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Muhlenbergia richardsonis" order="Poales" pageId="27" pageNumber="150" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="richardsonis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="150">Muhlenbergia richardsonis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Trin.) Rydb., a wide ranging North American species, is also morphologically similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. fastigiata" order="Poales" pageId="27" pageNumber="150" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="fastigiata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="150">M. fastigiata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in most characters, although 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. richardsonis" order="Poales" pageId="27" pageNumber="150" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="richardsonis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="150">M. richardsonis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a taller habit and differes in leaf anatomy (
<bibRefCitation author="Morden, CW" journalOrPublisher="Nordic Journal of Botany" pageId="58" pageNumber="181" refId="B19" refString="Morden, CW, 1985. A biosystematic study of the Muhlenbergiarepens complex (Poaceae). PhD. Dissertation. Texas A&amp;M University, College Station." title="A biosystematic study of the Muhlenbergiarepens complex (Poaceae). PhD. Dissertation. Texas A &amp; M University, College Station." year="1985">Morden 1985</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Morden, CW" journalOrPublisher="Sida" pageId="58" pageNumber="181" pagination="349 - 365" refId="B21" refString="Morden, CW, Hatch, SL, 1996. Morphological variation and synopsis of the Muhlenbergia repens complex (Poaceae). Sida 17: 349 - 365" title="Morphological variation and synopsis of the Muhlenbergia repens complex (Poaceae)." volume="17" year="1996">Morden and Hatch 1996</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Aciachne" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Aciachne acicularis" order="Poales" pageId="27" pageNumber="150" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="species" species="acicularis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="150">Aciachne acicularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken originalValue="Lægaard">Laegaard</normalizedToken>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. pulvinata" pageId="27" pageNumber="150" rank="species" species="pulvinata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="150">A. pulvinata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Benth., two small, compact, mat-forming perennials, can also be mistaken for 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="M." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="M. fastigiata" order="Poales" pageId="27" pageNumber="150" phylum="Angiospermae" rank="species" species="fastigiata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="150">M. fastigiata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, both species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bentham" authorityYear="1881" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Aciachne" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Aciachne" order="Poales" pageId="27" pageNumber="150" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="27" pageNumber="150">Aciachne</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bentham" authorityYear="1861" genus="Pooideae" lsidName="" pageId="27" pageNumber="150" rank="genus" subfamily="Pooideae">Pooideae</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bentham" authorityYear="1861" genus="Pooideae" lsidName="" pageId="27" pageNumber="150" rank="tribe" tribe="Stipeae">Stipeae</taxonomicName>
) have longer spikelets ranging from 3.8-6 mm long, glumes that are 3-5-veined, and tightly overlapping lemma margins (
<bibRefCitation author="Renvoize, SA" journalOrPublisher="Phytologia" pageId="59" pageNumber="182" refId="B52" refString="Renvoize, SA, 1998. Gramineas de Bolivia. The Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew, 1-644." title="Gramineas de Bolivia. The Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew, 1 - 644." year="1998">Renvoize 1998</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Giraldo-Canas, D" journalOrPublisher="Caldasia" pageId="58" pageNumber="181" pagination="269 - 302" refId="B7" refString="Giraldo-Canas, D, Peterson, P, 2009. El genero Muhlenbergia (Poaceae: Chloridoideae: Cynodonteae: Muhlenbergiinae) en Colombia. Caldasia 31: 269 - 302" title="El genero Muhlenbergia (Poaceae: Chloridoideae: Cynodonteae: Muhlenbergiinae) en Colombia." volume="31" year="2009">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Giraldo-Cañas">Giraldo-Canas</normalizedToken>
and Peterson 2009
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="27" pageNumber="150">
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Muhlenbergia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Muhlenbergia fastigiata" order="Poales" pageId="27" pageNumber="150" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="fastigiata">
